Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

A sales forecast is a prediction of future sales revenue based on historical data, industry trends, and the status of the current sales pipeline. Businesses use the sales forecast to estimate weekly, monthly, quarterly, and annual sales totals. A company needs to make an accurate sales forecast as it adds value across an organization and helps the different verticals to chalk out their future course of action.

Forecasting helps an organization plan its sales operations by region and provides valuable insights to the supply chain team regarding the procurement of goods and materials. An accurate sales forecast process has many benefits which include improved decision-making about the future and reduction of sales pipeline and forecast risks. Moreover, it helps to reduce the time spent in planning territory coverage and establish benchmarks that can be used to assess trends in the future.

Objective¶

SuperKart is a retail chain operating supermarkets and food marts across various tier cities, offering a wide range of products. To optimize its inventory management and make informed decisions around regional sales strategies, SuperKart wants to accurately forecast the sales revenue of its outlets for the upcoming quarter.

To operationalize these insights at scale, the company has partnered with a data science firmnot just to build a predictive model based on historical sales data, but to develop and deploy a robust forecasting solution that can be integrated into SuperKarts decision-making systems and used across its network of stores.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the various products and stores.The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • Product_Id - unique identifier of each product, each identifier having two letters at the beginning followed by a number.
  • Product_Weight - weight of each product
  • Product_Sugar_Content - sugar content of each product like low sugar, regular and no sugar
  • Product_Allocated_Area - ratio of the allocated display area of each product to the total display area of all the products in a store
  • Product_Type - broad category for each product like meat, snack foods, hard drinks, dairy, canned, soft drinks, health and hygiene, baking goods, bread, breakfast, frozen foods, fruits and vegetables, household, seafood, starchy foods, others
  • Product_MRP - maximum retail price of each product
  • Store_Id - unique identifier of each store
  • Store_Establishment_Year - year in which the store was established
  • Store_Size - size of the store depending on sq. feet like high, medium and low
  • Store_Location_City_Type - type of city in which the store is located like Tier 1, Tier 2 and Tier 3. Tier 1 consists of cities where the standard of living is comparatively higher than its Tier 2 and Tier 3 counterparts.
  • Store_Type - type of store depending on the products that are being sold there like Departmental Store, Supermarket Type 1, Supermarket Type 2 and Food Mart
  • Product_Store_Sales_Total - total revenue generated by the sale of that particular product in that particular store

Observation:¶

The summary statistics of categorical variables provide valuable insights into cardinality, dominance patterns, and encoding considerations.

Feature-wise Interpretation¶

  • Product_Id

    • Unique values: 8,763 (100% unique)
    • Each product appears exactly once, indicating this is a pure identifier rather than a predictive feature.
    • Including it directly in modeling may add noise without predictive value and increase deployment complexity.

  • Product_Sugar_Content

    • 4 distinct categories with Low Sugar dominating (~56%)

    • This imbalance suggests:

      • Strong market preference or labeling bias
      • The feature remains informative but should be monitored for category imbalance effects.

  • Product_Type

    • 16 categories with Fruits and Vegetables as the most frequent
    • Moderate cardinality makes it suitable for One-Hot Encoding without excessive dimensionality.

  • Store_Id

    • 4 unique stores, with OUT004 accounting for more than half of the data
    • This skew indicates store-level dominance, which can significantly influence sales predictions.

  • Store_Size

    • 3 categories, heavily dominated by Medium stores
    • Low cardinality and strong interpretability make it an excellent candidate for encoding.

  • Store_Location_City_Type

    • 3 tiers, with Tier 2 representing the majority
    • Reflects realistic urban distribution and is likely to be a strong sales driver.

  • Store_Type

    • 4 categories, dominated by Supermarket Type2
    • Suggests operational scale differences across store types that can influence revenue.

Modeling & Deployment Implications¶

  • High-cardinality identifier columns (Product_Id) should be:

    • Excluded from modeling or
    • Used only for tracking, not prediction

  • Low-to-moderate cardinality features are:

    • Ideal for One-Hot Encoding
    • Stable and safe for deployment pipelines

  • Dominant categories indicate:

    • Potential class imbalance, which should be considered when interpreting feature importance

Conclusion: The categorical variables exhibit clear dominance patterns and manageable cardinality, aligning well with retail business dynamics. Careful feature selectionespecially excluding pure identifierscombined with consistent encoding will ensure a robust, interpretable, and deployment-ready SuperKart sales prediction model.

numerical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns

summary_list = []

for col in numerical_cols:
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    outliers = df[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound)][col].count()

    summary_list.append({
        "Feature": col,
        "Mean": df[col].mean(),
        "Median": df[col].median(),
        "Std Dev": df[col].std(),
        "Skewness": df[col].skew(),
        "Kurtosis": df[col].kurtosis(),
        "IQR": IQR,
        "Lower Bound (Boxplot)": lower_bound,
        "Upper Bound (Boxplot)": upper_bound,
        "Outlier Count": outliers,
        "Min": df[col].min(),
        "Max": df[col].max()
    })

def histogram_boxplot(data=df, feature="", figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=30):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--", label="Mean"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-", label="Median"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# function to create labeled barplots
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=FutureWarning)

def labeled_barplot(data, feature="", perc=True, n=5):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
        hue=None,
        legend=False
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=10,
            xytext=(0, 3),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

  • The presence of strong correlations among store-level variables highlights the importance of handling multicollinearity, particularly for linear models.
  • From a deployment perspective, these relationships align with business logic, improving model interpretability and stakeholder trust.

Conclusion: The correlation heatmap confirms that both product characteristics and store context play significant roles in determining sales. Strong price and location effects dominate, while categorical and identifier features show limited linear influence. Overall, the correlation structure supports the feature selection strategy and validates the datasets suitability for robust sales prediction in the SuperKart deployment pipeline.

def detect_outliers_iqr_all(data):
    outlier_summary = {}
    numeric_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns

    for col in numeric_cols:
        Q1 = data[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = data[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        outliers = data[(data[col] < lower_bound) | (data[col] > upper_bound)]
        outlier_summary[col] = len(outliers)

    return outlier_summary

# Run it
outliers_count = detect_outliers_iqr_all(df)
print(outliers_count)

# Step 2: IQR Method
def detect_outliers_iqr(data, column):
    Q1 = data[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = data[(data[column] < lower) | (data[column] > upper)]
    print(f"{column}: {len(outliers)} outliers detected using IQR")
    return outliers, lower, upper

# Step 3: Z-score method (useful for normally distributed features)
from scipy import stats

def detect_outliers_zscore(data, column, threshold=3):
    z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(data[column].dropna()))
    outliers = data[z_scores > threshold]
    print(f"{column}: {len(outliers)} outliers detected using Z-score")
    return outliers

# Apply both methods
for col in num_cols:
    outliers_iqr, lower, upper = detect_outliers_iqr(df, col)
    outliers_z = detect_outliers_zscore(df, col)
    print(f"Suggested range for {col}: [{lower:.2f}, {upper:.2f}] (IQR method)")

# ================================
# MODEL EVALUATION FUNCTIONS
# ================================
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance
    """

    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(target, pred)

    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

    scoring="r2",
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=1
)

gb_grid.fit(X_train_processed, y_train)

best_gb = gb_grid.best_estimator_

print("Best Gradient Boosting Parameters:")
print(gb_grid.best_params_)

Fitting 5 folds for each of 16 candidates, totalling 80 fits
Best Gradient Boosting Parameters:
{'learning_rate': 0.1, 'max_depth': 4, 'n_estimators': 200, 'subsample': 0.8}

Observation:¶

  • The Gradient Boosting model was tuned using 16 hyperparameter combinations with 5-fold cross-validation, resulting in 80 total fits.

  • This cross-validated search ensures that the selected configuration performs consistently across different data splits and is not biased toward a single trainvalidation partition.

  • The best-performing Gradient Boosting parameters are:

    • learning_rate = 0.1 Provides a balanced step size, enabling stable learning while maintaining reasonable convergence speed.
    • n_estimators = 200 A sufficiently large number of boosting stages to capture complex patterns without excessive overfitting.
    • max_depth = 4 Allows each tree to model moderate feature interactions while controlling model complexity.
    • subsample = 0.8 Introduces stochasticity by training each tree on 80% of the data, which improves generalization and reduces variance.

  • From a biasvariance perspective, this configuration achieves a strong balance:

    • Shallow trees and subsampling help reduce overfitting.
    • A moderate learning rate with enough estimators ensures high predictive capacity.

  • From a business and deployment perspective, this setup offers:

    • High predictive accuracy
    • Robust generalization to unseen stores and products
    • Manageable training time and inference cost

Conclusion: The Gradient Boosting model tuning was efficient and well-calibrated, yielding a configuration that is both accurate and robust. This model is a strong candidate for comparison against the tuned Random Forest and for final selection in the SuperKart sales prediction pipeline.

%%writefile app.py
# ----------------------------------
# Initialize Flask app
# ----------------------------------
app = Flask(__name__)

# ----------------------------------
# Load model & preprocessing pipeline
# ----------------------------------
model = joblib.load("final_model.pkl")
preprocessor = joblib.load("preprocessing_pipeline.pkl")

EXPECTED_FEATURES = [
    "Product_Weight",
    "Product_Sugar_Content",
    "Product_Allocated_Area",
    "Product_Type",
    "Product_MRP",
    "Store_Id",
    "Store_Size",
    "Store_Location_City_Type",
    "Store_Type",
    "Store_Age"
]

# ----------------------------------
# Health check route
# ----------------------------------
@app.route("/", methods=["GET"])
def home():
    return jsonify({"status": "OK", "message": "SuperKart Backend Running"})

# ----------------------------------
# Prediction route
# ----------------------------------
@app.route("/predict", methods=["POST"])
def predict():
    try:
        data = request.get_json(force=True)

        missing = [f for f in EXPECTED_FEATURES if f not in data]
        if missing:
            return jsonify({"error": f"Missing fields: {missing}"}), 400

        input_df = pd.DataFrame([[data[f] for f in EXPECTED_FEATURES]],
                                columns=EXPECTED_FEATURES)

        processed = preprocessor.transform(input_df)
        prediction = model.predict(processed)[0]

        return jsonify({"prediction": round(float(prediction), 2)})

    except Exception as e:
        return jsonify({"error": str(e)}), 500

import os
import streamlit as st
import requests

PORT = int(os.environ.get("PORT", 7860))

st.set_page_config(
    page_title="SuperKart Sales Forecast",
    layout="centered"
)

st.title("SuperKart Sales Forecasting App")
st.write("Predict product-level sales revenue using a deployed ML model.")

BACKEND_API_URL = "https://monakariminezhad-superkart-backend.hf.space/predict"

st.subheader("Enter Product & Store Details")

product_weight = st.number_input("Product Weight", min_value=0.0, value=10.0)
product_sugar = st.selectbox("Product Sugar Content", ["Low Sugar", "Regular", "No Sugar"])
allocated_area = st.number_input("Product Allocated Area Ratio", 0.0, 1.0, 0.05)

product_type = st.selectbox(
    "Product Type",
    [
        "Dairy", "Frozen Foods", "Meat", "Snack Foods", "Soft Drinks",
        "Hard Drinks", "Baking Goods", "Health and Hygiene", "Bread",
        "Breakfast", "Canned", "Household", "Fruits and Vegetables",
        "Seafood", "Starchy Foods", "Others"
    ]
)

product_mrp = st.number_input("Product MRP", min_value=0.0, value=150.0)

store_id = st.selectbox("Store ID", ["OUT001", "OUT002", "OUT003", "OUT004"])
store_size = st.selectbox("Store Size", ["Small", "Medium", "High"])
store_city = st.selectbox("Store City Type", ["Tier 1", "Tier 2", "Tier 3"])
store_type = st.selectbox(
    "Store Type",
    ["Departmental Store", "Supermarket Type1", "Supermarket Type2", "Food Mart"]
)
store_age = st.number_input("Store Age (Years)", min_value=0, value=15)

if st.button("Predict Sales"):
    payload = {
        "Product_Weight": product_weight,
        "Product_Sugar_Content": product_sugar,
        "Product_Allocated_Area": allocated_area,
        "Product_Type": product_type,
        "Product_MRP": product_mrp,
        "Store_Id": store_id,
        "Store_Size": store_size,
        "Store_Location_City_Type": store_city,
        "Store_Type": store_type,
        "Store_Age": store_age
    }

    try:
        response = requests.post(BACKEND_API_URL, json=payload, timeout=10)
        if response.status_code == 200:
            st.success(f"Predicted Sales Revenue: **{response.json()['prediction']}**")
        else:
            st.error(response.text)
    except Exception as e:
        st.error(str(e))

Quick note:¶

The frontend component of the SuperKart application was deployed using a Docker-based Streamlit Space on Hugging Face. Although the Streamlit application launched successfully and bound to the designated port (as verified through container logs), the platform repeatedly reported the workload as unhealthy and terminated the deployment after a timeout.

This behavior was traced to a known limitation in Hugging Face Docker Spaces, where container health checks rely on immediate HTTP responses from the root endpoint. Streamlits internal routing and WebSocket-based initialization can delay or redirect such responses, leading to false-negative health check results despite the application being fully operational.

Importantly, this issue was not related to the application logic, machine learning model, or Docker configuration, but rather to platform-specific health-check expectations. The backend prediction API deployed independently on Hugging Face Spaces functioned correctly and remained accessible throughout the deployment process.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

1. Key Business Insights from the Model¶

1.1 Price (MRP) Is the Primary Sales Driver¶

The model reveals that Product MRP has the strongest positive relationship with total store sales. Higher-priced products tend to generate higher total sales, indicating that revenue growth at SuperKart is value-driven rather than volume-only driven.

Insight: Customers are willing to pay more for products perceived as higher value, quality, or necessity.

1.2 Product Weight Significantly Influences Sales¶

Product Weight shows a strong positive impact on sales, suggesting that larger pack sizes or higher-weight items contribute more to total revenue.

Insight: Customers prefer larger quantity purchases, especially for frequently consumed or staple products.

1.3 Store Location and Store Size Strongly Affect Performance¶

Sales are substantially influenced by:

  • Store Location City Type
  • Store Size
  • Store Type

Tier-2 locations and medium-to-large stores consistently outperform others.

Insight: Sales performance is structurally driven by store infrastructure and geographic context, not just product attributes.

1.4 Product Placement (Allocated Area) Shows Diminishing Returns¶

While shelf space allocation impacts sales, the relationship is weaker than price or weight and shows signs of diminishing returns beyond a certain range.

Insight: Simply increasing shelf space does not guarantee proportional sales growth.

1.5 Store Age Has Limited Direct Impact¶

Store age shows a weak negative correlation with sales, indicating that newer stores are not inherently disadvantaged.

Insight: Operational strategy and product mix matter more than store longevity.
